= 114 + 72 + 85 + 207 + 324 = 802

Initial thought: My Brick and Ore are both high-value resources (23 & 36).  
Wheat is by far the lowest-value (6). I have a surplus of 19 Wheat, and I don’t want to lose Sheep or Ore unnecessarily.  
I also have exactly 9 Brick, so extending to 10+ could potentially be useful, but each extra Brick only adds 23 in value whereas preserving Ore adds more.  
Therefore my first objective is to turn some low-value Wheat into higher-value resources (Brick, Ore, Sheep).

Let me open the negotiation with an attractive-looking offer built around Wheat.

[Offer: 5 Wheat, 2 Wood -> 3 Brick, 3 Ore]

rounds.response:
I think my initial offers were too generous to Player 1; they aren’t biting.  
My brick and ore are extremely valuable to me (23 and 36 value each), so any brick-for-brick or ore-for-ore swap is a no-go for me.  
Sheep is my only high-tier resource at 17 value and plentiful compared to my other ROI-friendly choices.  
Wheat and wood are worth a combined 6 + 9 = 15, barely better than a single brick.

Let’s pivot: offer Player 1 a bundle anchored by sheep—the asset I’m most willing to part with—while asking primarily for brick (still very valuable) and a little ore to keep the mid-tier balance right.

I’ll package 2 Sheep and 5 Wheat (total value 34 × 17 + 5 × 6 = 34) because 34 ≃ 3×23 (brick) and the added ore balances the demand curve.  

[Offer: 2 Sheep, 5 Wheat -> 3 Brick, 1 Ore]
